  "prompt": "The bond angle of Sulphur dioxide is greater than that of Ozone. Why?",
  "response": "The bond angle in sulfur dioxide (SO\u2082) is indeed greater than that in ozone (O\u2083). This difference can be explained through the principles of **Valence Shell Electron Pair Repulsion (VSEPR) theory** and the electronic structures of the two molecules.\n\n### **Electronic Structure and VSEPR Geometry**\n\n1. **Ozone (O\u2083):**\n   - **Lewis Structure:** Ozone has a resonance structure with a central oxygen atom bonded to two other oxygen atoms. The central oxygen has **one lone pair** of electrons.\n   - **Electron Domains:** There are three regions of electron density (two bonding pairs and one lone pair) around the central oxygen atom.\n   - **Geometry:** This arrangement leads to a **bent** molecular shape with a bond angle slightly less than 120\u00b0, typically around **117\u00b0**. The lone pair occupies more space, causing greater repulsion and thus reducing the bond angle.\n\n2. **Sulfur Dioxide (SO\u2082):**\n   - **Lewis Structure:** Sulfur dioxide has a central sulfur atom bonded to two oxygen atoms. The sulfur atom has **one lone pair** of electrons.\n   - **Electron Domains:** Similar to ozone, there are three regions of electron density (two bonding pairs and one lone pair) around the central sulfur atom.\n   - **Geometry:** This also results in a **bent** shape. However, the bond angle is larger, typically around **119\u00b0**.\n\n### **Reasons for the Larger Bond Angle in SO\u2082**\n\n1. **Atomic Size:**\n   - **Sulfur vs. Oxygen:** Sulfur is in the third period of the periodic table, making it larger than oxygen, which is in the second period. The larger size of sulfur allows the bonding pairs to spread out more, reducing electron pair repulsion and **increasing the bond angle**.\n\n2. **D-Orbitals and Expanded Octet:**\n   - **Sulfur\u2019s Ability to Expand Its Octet:** Sulfur can utilize **d-orbitals** to accommodate extra electron density, which can help in delocalizing electron pairs and reducing lone pair repulsion around the central atom. This contributes to a **greater bond angle** in SO\u2082 compared to O\u2083.\n\n3. **Lone Pair Repulsion:**\n   - **Less Repulsion in SO\u2082:** The lone pair on sulfur in SO\u2082 experiences less repulsion compared to the lone pair on oxygen in O\u2083. This reduced repulsion allows the bonding pairs to adopt a wider angle.\n\n4. **Resonance Structures:**\n   - **Stabilization through Resonance:** SO\u2082 has resonance structures that help stabilize the molecule and distribute electron density more evenly, contributing to a larger bond angle.\n\n### **Conclusion**\n\nThe slightly larger bond angle in sulfur dioxide compared to ozone is primarily due to the larger size of the sulfur atom, its ability to utilize d-orbitals for bonding, and the resultant reduction in lone pair repulsion around the central atom. These factors allow the bonding pairs in SO\u2082 to adopt a wider angle, resulting in a bond angle greater than that in ozone.\n\n**Summary:**  \nSulfur dioxide has a wider bond angle than ozone because the larger sulfur atom and its bonding structure experience less lone pair repulsion on the central atom than ozone\u2019s smaller oxygen center. This allows the O\u2013S\u2013O angle in SO\u2082 to be greater than the O\u2013O\u2013O angle in O\u2083.",
